            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is Hubble’s law?</h2>
              <p>
                Hubble’s law describes the observed expansion of the universe.
                It states that the recession velocity of a distant galaxy is
                proportional to its distance from us:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">\( v = H_0 \, d \)</p>
                <ul class="text-sm mt-2">
                  <li><strong>v</strong> – recession velocity (km/s)</li>
                  <li><strong>H₀</strong> – Hubble constant (e.g. km/s/Mpc)</li>
                  <li><strong>d</strong> – distance to the galaxy (Mpc)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                This simple linear relation is one of the key pieces of evidence
                that the universe is expanding. For every additional megaparsec
                of distance, the recession velocity increases by roughly 70 km/s
                (using a typical value of H₀ ≈ 70 km/s/Mpc).
              </p>

              <h2>Formulas used in this Hubble’s law calculator</h2>
              <h3>1. Velocity from distance</h3>
              <p>If you know the distance, the recession velocity is</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">\( v = H_0 \, d \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Distance from velocity</h3>
              <p>Rearranging Hubble’s law gives</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">\( d = \dfrac{v}{H_0} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Redshift approximation</h3>
              <p>
                For small redshift \( z \ll 1 \), the recession velocity is
                approximately \( v \approx z c \), where \( c \) is the speed of
                light. Combining this with Hubble’s law:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  \( v \approx z c \) &nbsp; and &nbsp; \( v = H_0 d \) &nbsp; ⇒
                  &nbsp; \( z \approx \dfrac{H_0 d}{c} \approx \dfrac{v}{c} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This calculator uses this small‑z approximation to convert
                between redshift, velocity, and distance. For high redshift
                (e.g. z &gt; 0.2), you should use a full cosmology calculator
                that integrates over the expansion history of the universe.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Approximate lookback time</h3>
              <p>
                For small redshift, the lookback time (how long the light has
                been traveling) can be estimated using
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  \( t_{\text{lookback}} \approx \dfrac{z}{H_0} \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs mt-1 text-gray-600">
                  (with H₀ converted to s⁻¹ and then to billions of years)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is a rough estimate but useful for building intuition in
                classroom settings.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical values of the Hubble constant H₀</h2>
              <p>
                Modern measurements of H₀ cluster in the range 67–74 km/s/Mpc,
                depending on the method:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Planck CMB data:</strong> H₀ ≈ 67.4 km/s/Mpc</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Distance ladder (Cepheids, supernovae):</strong> H₀ ≈
                  73 km/s/Mpc
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Textbook / classroom value:</strong> H₀ ≈ 70 km/s/Mpc
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator lets you enter any value and unit for H₀, so you
                can explore how different choices affect inferred distances and
                velocities.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose a galaxy is observed at a distance of 100 Mpc, and we
                adopt \( H_0 = 70 \,\text{km/s/Mpc} \).
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Compute the recession velocity:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                      \( v = H_0 d = 70 \times 100 = 7000 \,\text{km/s} \)
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Estimate the redshift:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                      \( z \approx \dfrac{v}{c} = \dfrac{7000}{299{,}792}
                      \approx 0.023 \)
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Entering 100 Mpc and H₀ = 70 km/s/Mpc into the calculator will
                reproduce these values and also show the approximate lookback
                time.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations of Hubble’s law</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Peculiar velocities:</strong> Nearby galaxies have
                  random motions (hundreds of km/s) that can be comparable to
                  the Hubble flow, so distances inferred from Hubble’s law alone
                  can be noisy at small d.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>High redshift:</strong> At large z the expansion rate
                  changes with time, so the linear relation v = H₀ d is no
                  longer accurate. Use a full cosmology calculator in that
                  regime.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choice of cosmological parameters:</strong> Distances
                  at high redshift depend on Ω<sub>m</sub>, Ω<sub>Λ</sub>,
                  curvature, and the dark‑energy model.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is Hubble’s law the same as the Doppler effect?</h3>
              <p>
                The redshift of distant galaxies can be interpreted
                mathematically like a Doppler shift, but in modern cosmology it
                is better understood as the stretching of space itself. Hubble’s
                law describes this cosmological redshift, not motion through a
                static space.
              </p>

              <h3>Can Hubble’s law give negative velocities?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Some nearby galaxies (like Andromeda) are gravitationally
                bound to the Milky Way and are moving toward us, giving a
                negative recession velocity and negative redshift. In those
                cases Hubble’s law does not apply in a simple way.
              </p>

              <h3>Why do different sources quote different H₀ values?</h3>
              <p>
                Different measurement techniques (cosmic microwave background
                vs. local distance ladder) currently give slightly different
                values of H₀. This “Hubble tension” is an active area of
                research and may hint at new physics or subtle systematics.
              </p>
            </section>
